SIMPLE: hop
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hop
<hw>Hop</hw> <pr>(h⟦ocr⟧p)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Hopped</conjf> <pr>(h⟦ocr⟧pt)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Hopping</conjf> <pr>(h⟦ocr⟧p"p⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph>
<ety>[OE. <ets>hoppen</ets> to hop, leap, dance, AS. <ets>hoppian</ets>;
akin to Icel. & Sw. <ets>hoppa</ets>, Dan. <ets>hoppe</ets>, D.
<ets>huppelen</ets>, G. <ets>h⟦uum⟧pfen</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To move by successive leaps, as toads do; to spring or jump on one
foot; to skip, as birds do.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Birds] <qex>hopping</qex> from spray to spray.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To walk lame; to limp; to halt.</def>
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To dance.</def> <rj><au>Smollett.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hop</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hop
<hw>Hop</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A leap on one leg, as of a
boy; a leap, as of a toad; a jump; a spring.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A dance; esp., an informal dance of ball.</def>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Hop, skip and jump</b></col>, <col><b>Hop, step and
a jump</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Hop, step and
jump</b></col></mcol>, <sn>1.</sn> <cd>a game or athletic sport in which
the participants cover as much ground as possible by a hop, stride, and
jump in succession.</cd> <sn>2.</sn> <cd>a short distance.</cd></cs>
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hop</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hop
<hw>Hop</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>hoppe</ets>; akin to D.
<ets>hop</ets>, <ets>hoppe</ets>, OHG. <ets>hopfo</ets>, G.
<ets>hopfen</ets>; cf. LL. <ets>hupa</ets>, W. <ets>hopez</ets>, Armor.
<ets>houpez</ets>, and Icel. <ets>humall</ets>, SW. & Dan.
<ets>humle</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A climbing
plant (<spn>Humulus Lupulus</spn>), having a long, twining, annual
stalk. It is cultivated for its fruit (hops).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The catkin or strobilaceous fruit of the hop, much
used in brewing to give a bitter taste.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The fruit of the dog-rose. See
<er>Hip</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Hop back</b></col>. <fld>(Brewing)</fld> <cd>See under
1st <er>Back</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Hop clover</b></col>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a species of yellow clover having heads like hops
in miniature (<spn>Trifolium agrarium</spn>, and <spn>Trifolium
procumbens</spn>).</cd> -- <col><b>Hop flea</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a small flea beetle (<spn>Haltica
concinna</spn>), very injurious to hops.</cd> -- <col><b>Hop
fly</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>an aphid (<spn>Phorodon
humuli</spn>), very injurious to hop vines.</cd> -- <col><b>Hop froth
fly</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>an hemipterous insect
(<spn>Aphrophora interrupta</spn>), allied to the cockoo spits. It often
does great damage to hop vines.</cd> -- <col><b>Hop hornbeam</b></col>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>an American tree of the genus <gen>Ostrya</gen>
(<spn>Ostrya Virginica</spn>) the American ironwood; also, a European
species (<spn>Ostrya vulgaris</spn>).</cd> -- <col><b>Hop moth</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a moth (<spn>Hypena humuli</spn>), which in the
larval state is very injurious to hop vines.</cd> -- <col><b>Hop
picker</b></col>, <cd>one who picks hops.</cd> -- <col><b>Hop
pole</b></col>, <cd>a pole used to support hop vines.</cd> --
<col><b>Hop tree</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a small American tree
(<spn>Ptelia trifoliata</spn>), having broad, flattened fruit in large
clusters, sometimes used as a substitute for hops.</cd> -- <col><b>Hop
vine</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>the climbing vine or stalk of the
hop.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hop</ent>⟦br⟧

